THIS OPINION HAS NO PRECEDENTIAL VALUE.Â  IT SHOULD NOT BE CITED OR RELIED ON AS PRECEDENT IN ANY PROCEEDING EXCEPT AS PROVIDED BY RULE 239(d)(2), SCACR.
THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA
In The Court of Appeals

  
    
      
Insulation Supply Company, Inc.,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Respondent,
      
    
  

v.

  
    
      
Anderson Area Medical Center, Inc.,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Appellant.
      
    
  


Appeal From Anderson County
Alexander S. Macaulay, Circuit Court Judge

Unpublished Opinion No. 2005-UP-300
Submitted April 1, 2005 â€“ Filed April 27, 2005

AFFIRMED


  
    
      
Stephen M. Reams, of Atlanta and Todd R. Davidson andÂ  D. Michael Henthorne, both of Anderson, for Appellant.
Todd Raymond Ellis, Smith Ellis &amp; Stuckey, PA, of Columbia, for Respondent.
      
    
  

PER CURIAM:Â  Anderson Area Medical Center, Inc. appeals the trial courtâ€™s judgment in favor of Insulation Supply Company, Inc. (â€œISCâ€) in a collection action for work completed at the behest of ISC by its subcontractor, Aesthetic Designs, Inc. (â€œADIâ€).Â  Anderson Medical argues the trial court erred in (1) allowing ISC to recover because ISC was not properly licensed and (2) in calculating the recovery amount.Â  We affirm.1
FACTUAL/PROCEDURAL BACKGROUND
In July 2000, Anderson Medicalâ€™s facility was facing action by the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control (DHEC) regarding fireproofing and fire-stopping concerns.Â  To avoid being fined or closed, Anderson Medical needed to repair areas of insufficient or failed fireproofing and fire-stopping material at its Health Campus facility.Â  Anderson Medicalâ€™s general contractor, Beers Construction, did not come back and remedy the fireproofing problems when initially demanded.Â  Anderson Medical then contacted ISC about performing the work.Â &nbsp; 
ISC is an insulation company that had previously contracted with Anderson Medical on over forty projects since 1996 for the installation and removal of insulation and asbestos as well as, through a subcontractor, for fireproofing services.Â  Tripp Morris, the vice-president of projects at ISC, testified he met with Anderson Medical representative Mr. Chapman, toured the area where the problems existed, and was asked to begin work on the project right away, or that day if possible.Â  Morris informed Chapman that ISC did not perform fireproofing work but subbed out that type of work, that ISCâ€™s regular fireproofing subcontractor was unavailable and that ISC did not have its own crews available to start the work immediately.Â  Chapman asked Morris to find someone to get on the job so Anderson Medical could avoid DHEC sanctions.Â  Morris then suggested to Chapman that a good candidate for the job would be Charles Chason, owner of ADI.Â  Morris informed Chapman that ADI was a general carpentry contractor that had no fireproofing experience, but Chason was reputable, and the company was based there in Anderson so it would cut down on hotel and per diem charges of employees that would be incurred if they used ISCâ€™s employees.Â  
Morris, Chason and Chapman met at the Health Campus facility where Chapman reiterated the need to get the job started and asked for a proposal.Â  On July 22, 2000, Morris forwarded to Anderson Medical ADIâ€™s proposal to ISC.Â  The proposal set forth ADIâ€™s hourly rates and provided ISC would supply all fireproofing materials and application equipment while ADI would supply all labor for the repair work and all labor and materials to clean the work areas.Â  Morris told Chapman ISC would charge Anderson Medical cost plus 20% to perform the work.Â  The plan was for ISC and ADI to begin work on the deficient areas so that Anderson Medical would not be fined, and to work until the projectâ€™s general contractor, Beers Construction, could come back in and complete the work.Â  ADI was told to proceed with the project.Â  
At the beginning of the project, Morris was at Anderson Medical twice a week to oversee the work and to ensure ADI met the hospitalâ€™s requirements.Â  Whenever he made site visits, he would check the areas worked on for deficiencies and make sure there were no problems and that Anderson Medical was satisfied.Â  Between November 2000 and March 2001, ISC sent three invoices to Anderson Medical demanding payment of a total of $294,829 for the work performed.Â  After DHEC apparently became satisfied with the progress on the fireproofing problems, Anderson Medical terminated ISC and ADIâ€™s work on the project, but refused to pay the submitted invoices.Â  Thereafter, in January 2002, Beers Construction and its fireproofing contractor undertook the remaining remedial repairs.Â  
ISC brought suit against Anderson Medical alleging causes of action of breach of their agreement and quantum meruit.Â  The trial court, sitting without a jury, determined the charges of ISC, with an adjustment for some misapplication, were reasonable and proper and ordered Anderson Medical to pay $278,909.19.Â  Anderson Medical filed a motion to alter or amend pursuant to Rule 59(e), SCRCP, arguing ISC failed to abide by South Carolina contractor licensing requirements because ADI held only a Group Two license and ISC failed to supervise ADI as required by S.C. Code Ann. Â§ 40-11-270, thereby precluding recovery in this case.Â  The trial court denied Anderson Medicalâ€™s motion to alter or amend and this appeal followed.Â  
STANDARD OF REVIEW
In an action at law, tried without a jury, the appellate courtâ€™s jurisdiction is limited to the correction of errors of law and the trial judgeâ€™s findings of fact will not be disturbed on appeal unless found to be without evidence that reasonably supports his findings.Â  Kemp V. Rawlings, 358 S.C. 28, 34, 594 S.E.2d 845, 848 (2004).Â  The trial judgeâ€™s findings are equivalent to those of a jury in an action at law.Â  King v. PYA/Monarch, Inc., 317 S.C. 385, 389, 453 S.E.2d 885, 888 (1995).
LAW/ANALYSIS
I.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; South Carolina Contractorâ€™s Licensing Statutes
